originPortalInfo.title: Love Park Pavilion
originPortalInfo.description: Designed by gh3* and fabricated by Eventscape, this 5-metre-high trellised pavilion anchors Toronto’s Love Park, which opened in June 2023. Over time, the wisteria will envelop the pavilion and provide welcome shade for activities below.

originPortalInfo.title: Raccoon on the Prowl
originPortalInfo.description: This raccoon - affectionately known in Toronto as a 'trash panda' - can be found prowling on the east side of Love Park. It is 1 of 9 bronze cast animal sculptures that you can discover throughout the park. All of the animals are native to Canada and photo references of real animals were used for each model. The sculptures were designed by artists Marina Guglielmi and Tyler Balko from Maker Technical Sculpture Services Inc. Toronto has often been dubbed 'the raccoon capital of the world.'

originPortalInfo.title: Westin Harbour Castle Installation
originPortalInfo.description:
Sarah Anne Johnson (2015) uses photography to explore communal experiences, taking a playful yet considered approach to the pursuit of the utopian. In this commissioned site-specific mural, Johnson's island scene -- part imaginary and part real -- echoes the adjacent natural landscape that lies just beyond the edge of the city.

Curated by Bonnie Rubenstein

Supported by Partners in Art, StreetARToronto, and The Westin Harbour Castle.

destinationPortalInfo.title: Westin Harbour Castle Installation
destinationPortalInfo.description:
Sarah Anne Johnson (2015) uses photography to explore communal experiences, taking a playful yet considered approach to the pursuit of the utopian. In this commissioned site-specific mural, Johnson's island scene -- part imaginary and part real -- echoes the adjacent natural landscape that lies just beyond the edge of the city.

Curated by Bonnie Rubenstein

Supported by Partners in Art, StreetARToronto, and The Westin Harbour Castle.

originPortalInfo.title: Chipmunk Hoarding Nuts
originPortalInfo.description: On the eastern edge of the heart-shaped pond in Toronto’s Love Park, this cute chipmunk sits on its hoard of golden nuts. (Even the nuts are heart-shaped - how adorable is that?) This is 1 of 9 bronze cast animal sculptures that you can discover throughout the park, which opened in June 2023. Photo references of real animals (all native to Canada) were used for each model. The sculptures were designed by artists Marina Guglielmi and Tyler Balko from Maker Technical Sculpture Services Inc.

originPortalInfo.title: Shore Stories
originPortalInfo.description: Unveiled in 2012, this 80-foot long mosaic mural titled ‘Shore Stories’ was designed and constructed by 18 Toronto youth artists under the guidance of Cristina Delago. Delago partnered with Arts for Children and Youth (now VIBE Arts) on this project. The mural is made of tiles, glass, pebbles and mirror, and depicts the Toronto waterfront’s local history.

originPortalInfo.title: "South Wind" (1987)
originPortalInfo.description:
William McElcheran (1927-1999) was a Canadian designer and sculptor. The bas-relief of green marble stands 7.5 m high and 7.5 m wide. It is located in the main lobby of 20 Bay St, the north building of Waterpark Place. 

"Life-size sculptures of a landed gull and a cat are affixed to the elevator lobby floor, and if you ask for directions to this sculpture, people who work in the building may tell you to look for the cat. Details like this are what catch people's attention." -- John Warkentin, _Creating Memory: A Guide to Outdoor Public Sculpture in Toronto_ (2010)
